This paper investigates the influence of national culture on people's online questioning and answering behavior in CQA services. It uses empirical data analysis to measure cultural metrics defined in Geert Hofstede's cultural dimensions and Robert Levine's Pace of Life. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which focuses on the study of social networks and their impact on information dissemination, user behavior, and social interactions. 

The paper also analyzes behavioral cultural differences in community question answering platforms, which could fall under the sub-categories of cs.CY (Computers and Society) and cs.CSCW (Computer-Supported Cooperative Work). 

Furthermore, the paper uses natural language processing techniques to analyze the content of questions and answers, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language). 

Finally, the paper discusses power inequality and privacy concerns in different national cultures, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.SOC (Computational Social Science).
